Lab 1: DevSecOps Series - Version Control and Containerization
Learning Objectives
By the end of this lab, students will be able to:

• Install and configure Docker and Podman containerization platforms • Understand the security differences between Docker and Podman regarding root privileges • Create and manage containers using both Docker and Podman • Set up a Git repository with proper version control practices • Differentiate between Git Workflow and Forking Workflow methodologies • Integrate Jenkins CI/CD tool with Git repositories • Implement basic DevSecOps practices using open-source tools

Prerequisites
Before starting this lab, students should have:

• Basic understanding of Linux command line operations • Familiarity with terminal/command prompt usage • Basic knowledge of software development concepts • Understanding of what containers and version control systems are (conceptual level)

Lab Environment Setup
Ready-to-Use Cloud Machines: Al Nafi provides pre-configured Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Simply click Start Lab to access your dedicated environment. No need to build or configure your own virtual machine.

Your lab environment includes: • Ubuntu 20.04 LTS or later • Internet connectivity for downloading packages • Sudo privileges for installation tasks • Pre-installed text editors (nano, vim)

Task 1: Container Platform Installation and Comparison
Subtask 1.1: Installing Docker
Step 1: Update System Packages

sudo apt update
sudo apt upgrade -y
Step 2: Install Required Dependencies

sudo apt install apt-transport-https ca-certificates curl gnupg lsb-release -y
Step 3: Add Docker's Official GPG Key

curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /usr/share/keyrings/docker-archive-keyring.gpg
Step 4: Add Docker Repository

echo "deb [arch=$(dpkg --print-architecture) signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/docker-archive-keyring.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu $(lsb_release -cs) stable" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list > /dev/null
Step 5: Install Docker Engine

sudo apt update
sudo apt install docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-compose-plugin -y
Step 6: Start and Enable Docker Service

sudo systemctl start docker
sudo systemctl enable docker
Step 7: Verify Docker Installation

sudo docker --version
sudo docker run hello-world
Step 8: Add Current User to Docker Group (Optional)

sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
newgrp docker
Subtask 1.2: Installing Podman
Step 1: Install Podman

sudo apt update
sudo apt install podman -y
Step 2: Verify Podman Installation

podman --version
podman run hello-world
Step 3: Configure Podman Registries

sudo nano /etc/containers/registries.conf
Add the following content if not present:

[registries.search]
registries = ['docker.io', 'registry.fedoraproject.org', 'quay.io', 'registry.access.redhat.com', 'registry.centos.org']
Subtask 1.3: Demonstrating Security Differences
Step 1: Check Docker Container Root Privileges

Create a simple container with Docker:

docker run -it --name docker-test ubuntu:20.04 /bin/bash
Inside the container, check the user:

whoami
id
ps aux
exit
Step 2: Check Podman Container User Privileges

Create a similar container with Podman:

podman run -it --name podman-test ubuntu:20.04 /bin/bash
Inside the container, check the user:

whoami
id
ps aux
exit
Step 3: Compare Process Ownership

On the host system, check running processes:

# For Docker
docker run -d --name docker-nginx nginx:alpine
ps aux | grep nginx

# For Podman
podman run -d --name podman-nginx nginx:alpine
ps aux | grep nginx
Key Observation: Docker containers run as root by default, while Podman runs containers as the current user, providing better security isolation.

Subtask 1.4: Container Management Comparison
Step 1: Create and Manage Docker Containers

# Create a web server container
docker run -d -p 8080:80 --name docker-web nginx:alpine

# List running containers
docker ps

# Stop and remove container
docker stop docker-web
docker rm docker-web
Step 2: Create and Manage Podman Containers

# Create a web server container
podman run -d -p 8081:80 --name podman-web nginx:alpine

# List running containers
podman ps

# Stop and remove container
podman stop podman-web
podman rm podman-web
Task 2: Git Repository Setup and CI/CD Integration
Subtask 2.1: Installing Git and Initial Configuration
Step 1: Install Git

sudo apt update
sudo apt install git -y
Step 2: Configure Git

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
git config --global init.defaultBranch main
Step 3: Verify Git Configuration

git config --list
Subtask 2.2: Setting Up a Local Git Repository
Step 1: Create Project Directory

mkdir devsecops-project
cd devsecops-project
Step 2: Initialize Git Repository

git init
Step 3: Create Sample Application Files

Create a simple web application:

# Create HTML file
cat > index.html << EOF
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>DevSecOps Lab Project</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome to DevSecOps Lab</h1>
    <p>This is a sample application for demonstrating Git workflows.</p>
</body>
</html>
EOF

# Create Dockerfile
cat > Dockerfile << EOF
FROM nginx:alpine
COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/
EXPOSE 80
CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]
EOF

# Create README file
cat > README.md << EOF
# DevSecOps Lab Project

This project demonstrates:
- Git version control
- Container deployment
- CI/CD integration

## Usage
Build and run the container:
\`\`\`
docker build -t devsecops-app .
docker run -p 8080:80 devsecops-app
\`\`\`
EOF
Step 4: Add and Commit Files

git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit: Add sample web application"
Subtask 2.3: Understanding Git Workflow vs Forking Workflow
Git Workflow (Centralized)

Step 1: Create Feature Branch

git checkout -b feature/add-styling
Step 2: Make Changes

cat > style.css << EOF
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    background-color: #f0f0f0;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 20px;
}

h1 {
    color: #333;
    text-align: center;
}

p {
    color: #666;
    text-align: center;
    font-size: 18px;
}
EOF

# Update HTML to include CSS
cat > index.html << EOF
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>DevSecOps Lab Project</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome to DevSecOps Lab</h1>
    <p>This is a sample application for demonstrating Git workflows.</p>
    <p>Now with improved styling!</p>
</body>
</html>
EOF
Step 3: Commit Changes

git add .
git commit -m "Add CSS styling to web application"
Step 4: Merge Back to Main

git checkout main
git merge feature/add-styling
git branch -d feature/add-styling
Forking Workflow Simulation

Step 1: Create Bare Repository (Simulating Remote)

cd ..
git clone --bare devsecops-project devsecops-project.git
Step 2: Clone as Different Developer

git clone devsecops-project.git developer-fork
cd developer-fork
Step 3: Make Changes in Fork

git checkout -b feature/add-footer

cat >> index.html << EOF
    <footer>
        <p>&copy; 2024 DevSecOps Lab. All rights reserved.</p>
    </footer>
</body>
</html>
EOF
Step 4: Commit and Push Changes

git add .
git commit -m "Add footer to web application"
git push origin feature/add-footer
Subtask 2.4: Installing and Configuring Jenkins
Step 1: Install Java (Jenkins Prerequisite)

sudo apt update
sudo apt install openjdk-11-jdk -y
java -version
Step 2: Add Jenkins Repository

curl -fsSL https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable/jenkins.io-2023.key | sudo tee /usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc > /dev/null

echo deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc] https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable binary/ | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/jenkins.list > /dev/null
Step 3: Install Jenkins

sudo apt update
sudo apt install jenkins -y
Step 4: Start and Enable Jenkins

sudo systemctl start jenkins
sudo systemctl enable jenkins
Step 5: Configure Firewall (if needed)

sudo ufw allow 8080
sudo ufw status
Step 6: Access Jenkins Web Interface

# Get initial admin password
sudo cat /var/lib/jenkins/secrets/initialAdminPassword
Open web browser and navigate to: http://your-server-ip:8080

Subtask 2.5: Integrating Git with Jenkins
Step 1: Install Git Plugin in Jenkins

Access Jenkins web interface
Go to Manage Jenkins > Manage Plugins
Search for "Git Plugin" and install if not already installed
Restart Jenkins if required
Step 2: Create Jenkins Job

Click New Item
Enter job name: devsecops-project-build
Select Freestyle project
Click OK
Step 3: Configure Source Code Management

In job configuration, scroll to Source Code Management
Select Git
Enter repository URL: /path/to/your/devsecops-project.git
Set branch to build: */main
Step 4: Add Build Steps

Scroll to Build section
Click Add build step > Execute shell
Add the following script:
#!/bin/bash
echo "Starting DevSecOps build process..."

# Build Docker image
docker build -t devsecops-app:$BUILD_NUMBER .

# Run security scan (basic example)
echo "Running basic security checks..."
docker run --rm -v $(pwd):/app alpine:latest sh -c "cd /app && find . -name '*.html' -exec echo 'Checking: {}' \;"

# Test the application
echo "Testing application..."
docker run -d -p 8082:80 --name test-app-$BUILD_NUMBER devsecops-app:$BUILD_NUMBER
sleep 5
curl -f http://localhost:8082 || exit 1
docker stop test-app-$BUILD_NUMBER
docker rm test-app-$BUILD_NUMBER

echo "Build completed successfully!"
Step 5: Configure Build Triggers

In Build Triggers section
Check Poll SCM
Set schedule: H/5 * * * * (polls every 5 minutes)
Step 6: Save and Test

Click Save
Click Build Now to test the job
Subtask 2.6: Creating a Complete CI/CD Pipeline
Step 1: Create Jenkinsfile

In your project directory, create a Jenkinsfile:

cd ~/devsecops-project
cat > Jenkinsfile << 'EOF'
pipeline {
    agent any
    
    environment {
        DOCKER_IMAGE = 'devsecops-app'
        DOCKER_TAG = "${BUILD_NUMBER}"
    }
    
    stages {
        stage('Checkout') {
            steps {
                echo 'Checking out source code...'
                checkout scm
            }
        }
        
        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                echo 'Building Docker image...'
                script {
                    sh "docker build -t ${DOCKER_IMAGE}:${DOCKER_TAG} ."
                    sh "docker tag ${DOCKER_IMAGE}:${DOCKER_TAG} ${DOCKER_IMAGE}:latest"
                }
            }
        }
        
        stage('Security Scan') {
            steps {
                echo 'Running security scans...'
                script {
                    // Basic file security check
                    sh 'find . -name "*.html" -exec echo "Scanning: {}" \\;'
                    
                    // Check for common security issues
                    sh '''
                        echo "Checking for hardcoded secrets..."
                        grep -r "password\\|secret\\|key" . --exclude-dir=.git || echo "No obvious secrets found"
                    '''
                }
            }
        }
        
        stage('Test') {
            steps {
                echo 'Running tests...'
                script {
                    sh """
                        docker run -d -p 8083:80 --name test-container-${BUILD_NUMBER} ${DOCKER_IMAGE}:${DOCKER_TAG}
                        sleep 10
                        curl -f http://localhost:8083 || exit 1
                        docker stop test-container-${BUILD_NUMBER}
                        docker rm test-container-${BUILD_NUMBER}
                    """
                }
            }
        }
        
        stage('Deploy') {
            steps {
                echo 'Deploying application...'
                script {
                    sh """
                        # Stop existing container if running
                        docker stop devsecops-app-prod || true
                        docker rm devsecops-app-prod || true
                        
                        # Deploy new version
                        docker run -d -p 8084:80 --name devsecops-app-prod ${DOCKER_IMAGE}:${DOCKER_TAG}
                        echo "Application deployed at http://localhost:8084"
                    """
                }
            }
        }
    }
    
    post {
        always {
            echo 'Cleaning up...'
            sh "docker image prune -f"
        }
        success {
            echo 'Pipeline completed successfully!'
        }
        failure {
            echo 'Pipeline failed!'
        }
    }
}
EOF
Step 2: Commit Pipeline Configuration

git add Jenkinsfile
git commit -m "Add Jenkins pipeline configuration"
Step 3: Create Pipeline Job in Jenkins

In Jenkins, click New Item
Enter name: devsecops-pipeline
Select Pipeline
Click OK
In Pipeline section, select Pipeline script from SCM
Choose Git as SCM
Enter repository URL
Set branch: */main
Script Path: Jenkinsfile
Click Save
Step 4: Run the Pipeline

Click Build Now
Monitor the pipeline execution in Blue Ocean or Console Output
Troubleshooting Common Issues
Docker Issues
Permission Denied Error

# Add user to docker group
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
newgrp docker
Docker Service Not Running

sudo systemctl start docker
sudo systemctl status docker
Podman Issues
Registry Configuration Problems

# Check registries configuration
cat /etc/containers/registries.conf

# Test registry connectivity
podman search nginx
Git Issues
Authentication Problems

# Configure credentials
git config --global credential.helper store
Merge Conflicts

# Check status
git status

# Resolve conflicts manually, then
git add .
git commit -m "Resolve merge conflicts"
Jenkins Issues
Port Already in Use

# Check what's using port 8080
sudo netstat -tlnp | grep 8080

# Change Jenkins port if needed
sudo nano /etc/default/jenkins
# Change HTTP_PORT=8080 to HTTP_PORT=8081
sudo systemctl restart jenkins
Build Failures

Check Jenkins logs: sudo journalctl -u jenkins -f
Verify Docker permissions for Jenkins user
Ensure all required plugins are installed
Conclusion
In this comprehensive lab, you have successfully:

Container Security Understanding: You installed both Docker and Podman, experiencing firsthand how Podman provides enhanced security by running containers without root privileges, while Docker requires additional configuration for similar security posture.

Version Control Mastery: You set up Git repositories and learned the practical differences between centralized Git workflow and forking workflow, understanding when to use each approach in real-world development scenarios.

CI/CD Integration: You installed and configured Jenkins, creating both simple build jobs and comprehensive pipelines that integrate with your Git repositories, demonstrating the foundation of DevSecOps practices.

Security-First Approach: Throughout the lab, you implemented security considerations from the beginning, including container privilege management, code scanning, and secure deployment practices.

Why This Matters: These skills form the backbone of modern DevSecOps practices. Understanding container security differences helps you make informed decisions about deployment platforms. Git workflow knowledge enables effective team collaboration. Jenkins integration provides the automation foundation necessary for continuous integration and deployment, while maintaining security throughout the development lifecycle.

The combination of these technologies creates a robust foundation for implementing DevSecOps practices in any organization, ensuring that security is built into every step of the development and deployment process rather than being an afterthought.

